\expndtw3\cgrid the cauldron hook east of Nagano Prefecture, in Shikoku and }{\expnd0\expndtw0\cgrid in the mountains of Central Kyilsha, that is, in more marginal areas. The cauldron hook seems to have been in use already in }{\expnd0\expndtw2\cgrid the 
Yayoi period and later in the Tumuli period. Furthermore, }{\expnd0\expndtw-1\cgrid in the countryside there is an area with a hearth for cooking and }{\expnd0\expndtw-4\cgrid an area with a fire-place for the same purpose. In Eastern Japan }{\expnd0
\expndtw2\cgrid people rarely transport loads on their heads, but they do it in }{\expnd0\expndtw-1\cgrid Izu, Tshikawa, Niigata, and Miyagi. In Western Japan, however, }{\expnd0\expndtw0\cgrid this customs is found everywhere. Eastern and Western Japan h
