\expndtw-4\cgrid Japan. A change from clan federations to kinship associations is }{\expnd0\expndtw-3\cgrid hardly thinkable. In Western Japan the position of the maternal }{\expnd0\expndtw-4\cgrid uncle has always been high. All these differences between
 Eastern }{\expnd0\expndtw4\cgrid and Western Japan have their roots in a tribal difference. At }{\expnd0\expndtw-4\cgrid the end of the Heian time we find seven political parties each in }{\expnd0\expndtw1\cgrid Musashi and in Nasu. Western Japan never s
aw the formation }{\expnd0\expndtw0\cgrid of such parties. They are federations of patriarchal clans which }{\expnd0\expndtw1\cgrid are not based on blood relationship but on the relationship of lords and vassals. It was on this basis that the Minamoto cl
an }{had built up its power. Its opponents, the Taira, with West Japan }{\expnd-1\expndtw-7\cgrid as their dominion, never succeeded in building up clan federations. }{\expnd0\expndtw-3\cgrid Their organisational pattern was that of a hierarchically grade
